The Republican Party's strategy against Obama's re-election
Republican leaders have justified their policies with the need to fight electoral fraud.
The Brennan Center, however, calls such fraud a myth, saying that election fraud is less common in the U.S. than the number of people who die after lightning strikes.
In the last 10 years, Republican lawyers have recorded only 300 cases of voter fraud in the United States.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on electoral participation.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. has a responsibility to organize federal elections.
And in this spirit, most U.S. governments have been promulgating new laws since 2009 that make the process of electing or enrolling in the electoral roll more difficult.
This phenomenon has seen a surge since the November 2010 elections, during which 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states have been added.
As a result, in 2011 alone, 180 bills restricting voting rights in 41 states were submitted.
The new election laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws limit the period for early elections, invalidate the right to register on the electoral list on the day of the elections and remove the right to vote from citizens with registration in the criminal register.
Before the 2006 election, no U.S. state had required voters to submit a photo ID.
The first state to introduce this requirement was Indiana.
The Constitution of the Indian Act was confirmed by the U.S. Supreme Court in 2008.
Republican authorities rushed to extend this process to other states.
In the past two years, they have supported draft laws in 34 states to force voters to submit photo IDs.
It should be noted that, unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity card, such as a health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, i.e. 21 million people of voting age, do not own an identity card with a photo issued by the government of their state.
In addition, about five million new voters in 2012 do not have such an identity card.
In addition, obtaining the required identity card often costs more than a hundred dollars.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect mainly young people, members of minorities and low-income people.
25% of African-Americans, 15% of people with income under $35,000; 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters aged 18 to 29 therefore do not have the required photo ID.
And that's not all.
Students who are known as voters for their inclination to democratic candidates are not allowed to use their photo ID issued by their school in several states.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of hunting or fishing clubs who elect rather republican candidates to use the cards issued by these clubs in elections.
Prior to 2004, no state required proof of citizenship in elections.
The first such request was made by Arizona.
Since 2011, about 12 states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the number of votes cast by the Hispanic minority.
It should be noted that two out of three Hispanics prefer a democratic party.
In 2011, Republican lawmakers in eight states approved laws that abolish voter registration on election day.
In addition, they have restricted the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters who wish to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, during the 2004 general elections, campaigns for voter registration helped to register about 10 million people.
However, measures taken after 2009 caused a 17% drop in voter registration in 2010 compared to 2006.
Republican lawmakers in five other states have passed laws aimed at shortening the period for early elections.
For example, during the 2008 general election in Florida, African-Americans accounted for 33% of the electorate who voted in advance, even though African-American voters in that state were only 13%.
It was the same with the Spaniards.
They constituted only 11% of all voters, but 24% of the citizens voting in advance.
On the other hand, whites, who made up 76% of all voters, made up only 46% of voters who voted in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters have very strongly opposed the adoption of laws that restrict voter registration.
The Democratic governors blocked several bills with their veto.
In order to suspend the most controversial laws, the Attorney General of the United States even intervened.
Some of the damage has been reduced.
For example, laws requiring the presentation of an identity card with a photo were adopted by only 16 of the 34 states.
However, the newly introduced rules will undeniably complicate the exercise of voting rights in 2012.
Democratic critics primarily talk about the bias of the approved laws and consider them an obvious attempt to influence the outcome of the 2012 elections in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that the states where these laws were passed represent 171 of the 270 votes in the electorate needed to win the presidential election.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
But one thing is certain today: these new provisions will have an adverse impact on electoral participation.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Detection of prostate cancer: to undergo an examination or not?
The PSA test sometimes produced erroneous results that were incorrectly negative or even incorrectly positive, leading to unnecessary medical interventions.
All this further increased the hesitation of men who were already so reluctant to go to the examination at all.
To be examined or not?
We asked for the opinion of two experts.
Studies conducted in the USA showed a high level of contamination between the individual groups tested, so it is difficult to interpret these results and make valuable recommendations.
Another study, this time European, found a difference in mortality between patients who underwent the examination and those who did not.
This study also showed after a 12-year interval that those who did not go for the examination had a 30 to 40% higher risk of metastasis.
Therefore, I recommend testing from the age of 50 or from the age of 40 if your direct relative had prostate cancer.
Men of African-American descent are also more at risk.
The key is to make the right decision once the cancer is detected.
There are aggressive types of cancer and such types that are intractable.
Therefore, it is necessary to correctly explain to the patient the degree of danger of his type of cancer, to offer him possible alternatives, not necessarily to treat prostate cancer, which does not have an impact on life in the long term, and in these cases to focus on active supervision of the disease.
Today, many men who have been diagnosed with cancer are not treated because their type of cancer is not aggressive and does not threaten their lives.
Rather, we will suggest them to carry out active supervision, and in case of disease progression, we will offer them treatment.
Increasingly and with greater precision, we define criteria that help in deciding which species to treat and which not.
However, I recommend that the examination be carried out.
However, it is important to have an interview with a doctor and determine whether it is appropriate to undergo an examination or not.
