Higgs Boson Examined
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson caused a legitimate stir last summer.
There is an opinion that this boson is involved in the mechanism that is responsible for all the matter in the universe.
And it is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the standard model - our best or "least bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - which has not yet been empirically observed.
However, there is still no 100% certainty among physicists that it is a Higgs boson.
There is no doubt that we have an entirely new particle, which is very similar to the Higgs boson, as predicted by the standard model.
The new data published this week during the Great Physical Congress in Kyoto rather confirms it, but all the data is still missing in order to be absolutely sure.
However, let's assume it's a Higgs boson, because the risk of error seems small, and let's look at what it's actually about.
In this world, there is a completely indisputable law, according to which two things cannot occur at the same time in the same place.
This rule cannot be circumvented - and do not try too hard, otherwise you will hurt yourself.
Although particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that a similar law applies to it: the Pauli exclusion principle, according to which two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time, if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" roughly speaking creates some of their properties.
It further divides the physical particles into two categories.
On the one hand, we find orderly citizens, or fermions, who obediently adhere to the Pauli principle.
And at the other end, there are barefoot, mean anarchists who don't appreciate anything at all - certainly not this principle, which means they can safely be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are further divided into two groups according to the device (by the way absolutely amazing), which is The Particle Adventure, in the Berkeley laboratories: the mesons that we leave here unnoticed, and the "force particles" that propagate the great forces of nature and with which the Higgs boson is probably somehow related.
However, it must be said that these barefoot animals are not as exotic as one might think.
If you read this article, it is thanks to a boson with an unusual banality: a photon, or "particle of light", which is the "carrier" of electromagnetic force.
Because when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes its direction, it "disrupts" the electromagnetic field at this particular location, much like a pebble thrown into a pond.
From this "disruption" an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.) arises, and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore one of the bosons, "force carriers".
A more stable field
The same is true of the Higgs boson, except that a different field, the Higgs field, needs to be "disrupted" in order for this boson to appear.
This Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, very high energy values must be achieved, similar to the frozen level of the pond, only a very large boulder will cross.
For this reason, it is necessary to use such a huge part accelerator as the accelerator in the CERN laboratory - a large hadron accelerator with accelerator beams is a circle with a circumference of 27 km! - in order to develop such energy.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is useful again to clarify the relationship between Higgs and matter.
Not all particles or materials react with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, do so, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never keep away from itself on the refrigerator.
And still, not all particles react with the Higgs field: those that do have a certain mass, while others (such as a photon, let's look at it) don't.
And Mrs. Nov<0xC3><0xA1>kov<0xC3><0xA1> asks, what is all this research for, what will it "bring to us"?
From a scientific point of view, this is a validation of the Standard Model (SM), which allows physicists to examine any discrepancy between SM observations and predictions.
In addition, not many physicists literally wish that they could be found, because the slightest difference could open up the space of "new physics" and close some gaps in the model.
It should be noted that the model still has huge shortcomings, it does not bring any clarification of gravity (ooh!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the space mass (again ooh!).
However, the CERN device has not yet revealed such contradictions.
Reactions
The responses of these researches in the daily lives of Mr. and Mrs. Nov<0xC3><0xA1>k can only be very difficult to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that there will be none.
At the very beginning of the 1960s, the laser pioneers in Bell’s labs had no idea of the revolution their work would bring.
They assumed scientific use, but nothing else.
Physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who created the first permanent laser beam (previous beams were pulsed) in 1962, I have already said - the laser was initially considered such a "toy to the lab".
Just imagine...
And in addition, the application may also result from all the tools that surround the research.
For example, the same Willard Boyle created a small light sensor in 1969 during his work on optics.
This sensor, although Boyle initially did not plan it, now serves as the "eye" of all digital cameras in the world and earned him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities around the LHC necessarily have to change our lives, but it does mean that one really never knows...
