53% of patients who come to Victor-Gadbois’ home come from their homes, 47% from hospitals.
Problems with access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care that is designed to alleviate suffering once the patient reaches the final stage of their life, whether it is at home, in a hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois home and the Grand Montréal Home Palliative Care Society, specialize more or less exclusively in the care provided to cancer patients.
And it is this fundamental lack of access to health care in Quebec that has led many palliative care physicians to fear the adoption of a law on euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto has been in circulation, signed by leading experts in the field of palliative care, such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, in which they demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Québec health care system is not powerful enough to ensure everyone has access to quality palliative care before euthanasia can be accepted.
She says she recently experienced a patient who spent 14 days in the emergency room in tremendous pain without anyone taking the necessary steps to relieve her.
He fears that patients will not be asked to be killed because they are not receiving proper care.
And at the same time, many oncologists take care of their patients until the last moments, regardless of the unfavorable prognosis.
Hel<0xC3><0xA8>ne Richard's chances of survival were already very low when she left demanding chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was quitting treatment, she said she regretted stopping the fight, she told us.
And she told me it was over!
There is no all-powerful care
Dr. Martel estimates that 90% of patients who wish to die thank their doctors for failing to fulfill their wishes when a team of palliative bitches relieved their pain.
However, it must be said that palliative care is not all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Grand Montréal Society for Home Palliative Care, patients are prevented from treating pain in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often use palliative sedatives, which put the patient to sleep until the moment of death, whether by accident or whether the sedatives are constantly administered to him.
It is impossible to pretend that we do not perceive this part of suffering.
The patient, who will not be relieved of pain, will have more and more access to palliative sedatives.
Sick people who are not given a sedative always say the same thing: “I want to die.”
But that doesn’t necessarily mean “I want you to give me euthanasia,” it means “I want you to get rid of my pain.”
