The bitcoin exchange rate first reached a maximum of $30 (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>23) in June 2011, five months later it fell to $2, today it is at the limit of about ten dollars (an overview of the exchange rates is provided on the site bitcoincharts.com).
Compared to the global exchange for real money or financial products, this is nothing impressive.
And yet, the European Central Bank (ECB) is interested in this fact in its report on virtual finance, which was published in October.
Bitcoin is described as “the most successful virtual money,” “competing the dollar and the euro,” and “a pattern of regular money.”
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual money in that it is used as "credits" for the progression in a video game, which one acquires through the game or which one can purchase (and sometimes exchange back).
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
Each month, however, the central authority checks and processes individual communications.
In the case of Bitcoin, all nodes are book depositors, controllers, money issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users takes place in fact between two electronic addresses by e-mail.
However, the user can choose a different address for each payment, thereby ensuring anonymity.
The file of information related to this transaction is electronically signed by a dual-key encryption system.
The network can then verify the legitimacy of the transaction.
It is also possible to ensure that exchanged bitcoins exist in the public ledger of current accounts, which is distributed throughout the network.
The key phase lies in writing this new transaction into this book.
It is done by solving a mathematical task assigned to computers, the solver of which, a temporary central banker, will have the right to complete this additional line.
This is the phase of cutting a file; that is, transforming a huge file into a shorter and unique digital footprint.
Computers "take" this new transaction and add a number to it, only then the whole "cut".
The goal is to find a number that provides a specific imprint (very zero at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes will easily check its correctness.
The transaction will then appear indestructibly linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification would change the imprint.
If the user would like to pay twice the same money very quickly in a row (within ten minutes), the network will only confirm one of the two transactions - the other will be abandoned, because each of them has a different imprint.
The computer that solves the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
In order to avoid inflation, this reward is regularly divided by two, probably by the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is thus limited to 21 million, but they can be divided up to one hundred millionth, so there is room for margin.
The difficulty of the given task also increases with the increasing level of calculation.
The network has already experienced its ups and downs.
Websites that provide services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins stored have been stolen.
“The rubble used does not concern the protocol itself,” said Pierre Noizat, who founded Paymium, a real-money payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also checks the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But this problem also applies to cash.
Prominent players like Wikipedia reject gifts of this nature.
Others, like the WordPress blog platform, accept them.
Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel recently analyzed a book of current accounts and showed that almost 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, "huge discounts" were launched.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul to convert bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a pedagogical book on this money, has great confidence in the potential of this technology as a transactional network.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (with real money) or contactless mobile payment, but it uses the Bitcoin system to verify transactions that are therefore cheaper.
In addition, the holder manages his/her identity and can thus remain anonymous.
The system is easy to set up with traders, where there is no need to install new terminals or software.
It is enough to give an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by the phone, says Pierre Noizat, who assures that he already has thousands of users.
There is a general movement to challenge hierarchical systems and the transition to more horizontal systems.
“It’s going to be a while before Bitcoin gets through, but 2013 could be a decisive year,” he predicts.
In addition, the ECB’s report foresees a reassessment of the various risks that are now considered to be increased if this type of money is successful.
