Difficult work on the Egyptian Constitution
President Mohamed Morsi is playing another game of poker.
While Egypt remains the most divided in its history due to the proclamation of a constitution that temporarily grants it unlimited powers, he decided to play vabank.
On Wednesday, he announced, regardless of everyone else’s opinion, that the Constitutional Assembly would approve the final text the next day.
Less than a week ago, the Head of State granted the Assembly two more months to complete the necessary work.
For almost two years, Egypt has been using a provisional text, which has been supplemented many times, weakening the country's constitutional stability and leading to legal conjectures.
This new initiative has only further strengthened the country’s split.
From the opposition's point of view, the president persists in his "autocratic delirium", continues to "break his word" and " tramples the law".
But his supporters say it is a means to reverse the constitutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held in two weeks.
This is a very short period of time, which will force the Brotherhood to withdraw from the intention of the text to the Egyptians to clarify the article after the article.
It is also a way for the president to regain national and democratic legitimacy, while the whole country is being swept away by protests.
As confirmed in an interview with the American weekly Time, Mohamed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in favour.
Particularly because this hastily organised vote puts the Egyptian people before an ultimatum: "Either you approve my text, or I will retain unlimited powers", which should otherwise end after the approval of the new constitution.
And in this special atmosphere yesterday, 85 MPs of the aforementioned Constituent Assembly, with a large majority of Islamists, approved the text.
The majority of the Liberals were absent from the vote.
In mid-November, shortly before the proclamation of the constitution, they knocked on the door, saying they had no opportunity to assert their views.
Human rights defenders, civil society or members of religious minorities imitated their move.
In order to achieve a quorum, 11 alternates were promptly added yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising that the articles of the Constitution were often voted unanimously.
The commentators also paused on the fact that one of the few quarrels that day revolved around... prayer hours, when some members of the committee held the view that the hours in the meeting room were not properly set up.
The text, which was voted on last night, consists of 234 articles.
The subject matter of general attention, Article 2, remains ultimately consistent with the 1971 version of the Constitution and stipulates that "the principles of Sharia law are the main source of law".
Salafist parties, for whom the introduction of Islamic law is one of the essential requirements, hoped to replace the term "principles" with the term "rules", which would allow for stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been corrected is a sign of their goodwill and respect for other parts of Egyptian society.
“Hypocrisy,” the Liberals object, who see it as a rhetorical problem.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place through other articles.
They focus in particular on Article 220, which confers an advisory role on al-Azhar University, in particular on issues of checking the compliance of laws with Sharia law.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pommier, this is troubling because "the people called to express themselves are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
This is the beginning of the theocracy.”
Liberals are even more concerned by the fact that the next rector of the university should be less moderate than the current one.
"So far, there has been no concrete religious consequence.
With this constitution, Egypt remains a civil state.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not ulamas, but university workers, many of whom graduated from French schools," Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a paper on the constitutional transition in Egypt, said.
However, it agrees that "there may be contradictions with regard to the interpretation of Article 220 because the terms used in it belong to the religious dictionary.
In particular, there is a reference to "fiqh" [Islamic legal science, ed.].
And in the future, the question may arise as to the extent to which civilian judges are competent to speak out.”
The text approved yesterday is highly criticized, in addition to religious pages, because of the expanded powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood insists that there have been significant restrictions on them over the former regime.
Another controversial place: the powers vested in the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the army representatives, the verification of the defense budget will not be carried out by the parliament, but by the National Defense Council.
In addition, military courts will not prohibit the conduct of civilians, as required by the association for the protection of human rights.
These associations speak about their doubts in connection with the text, which they believe is directed against freedom.
The offence of blasphemy is maintained and the insult continues to be prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially for the press.
In addition, no article deals with the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef from Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture referred to in Article 36.
This word was not mentioned in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to deliver a televised speech last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state will then demonstrate on Saturday.
In Israel waiting for Ukrainian tourists holy places, the belly button of the world and the sea of saturated salt solution
The Promised Land combines the greatness of biblical truths, modern comfort, and the inviolability of nature.
AaF has identified the five most important reasons why you should visit Israel.
Worshiping the Holy Places
Visit the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all who enter into this “bath” will receive God’s mercy.
And Galileo - the place of Jesus' miracles: turning water into wine at the wedding, walking on the water, calming the storm and filling the nets.
Here, too, Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
But the most holy places are in Jerusalem.
The faithful will pass through the Path of Pain, or Jesus’ Cross (Latin: Via Dolorosa).
It begins at the fortress of Antonia - Pretoria - where the trial was held, it passes through the streets of the Old Town and leads to the Temple of the Holy Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha - to the place of the crucifixion, to the stone of the anointing and to the place where Jesus was buried.
Here is the symbolic Christian navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
And the monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem was built on the place where, according to Christian legend, a tree grew, from which they made a cross for the crucifixion of Jesus.
Jerusalem is also home to the most sacred site for Jews, the Wall of Wailing, the rest of the temple that was destroyed by the Romans in 70 C.E.
According to tradition, people of different faiths leave notes with wishes, which will then be fulfilled.
Take the path vertically
The ruins of the fortress of Masada remained a secret hiding place from the enemy, which Herod the Great built in 25 BC for his family.
The ruins are located on cliffs in the mountains at an altitude of 450 m above sea level.
Only those who are engaged in mountaineering can reach it with their own strength.
The rest will be taken to this historic mountain by a cable car.
And in the north of the country, at an altitude of 1600-2040 m, there is the famous ski resort Hermon, which experiences a huge influx of tourists in the winter months.
A shuttle bus transports tourists to this ski paradise from the foot of the hill.
The total length of the mountain slopes is 45 km.
According to ancient legend, pagan gods lived on the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
There are about 300 museums in this country.
You can’t visit all of them in one trip.
But at least five of them, the most interesting, are definitely worth a visit.
Among them is the Israel Museum, which is located near the Knesset (Parliament).
It contains ancient Qumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea Scrolls, found in the caves of the Judean Desert, as well as some 500,000 archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Tel Aviv Museum of Art is also worth a visit.
His paintings are widely represented by impressionists and expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall, Picasso.
In Akkon, you can visit the Al Basha Bath Museum, which presents visitors with several rooms of the ancient Turkish bath with figurines of bath users and spa nurses from that time.
In Caesarea, it is worth visiting the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire the statues of Dal<0xC3><0xAD> and Rodin.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are strictly refused.
The Fifth Museum, the Yad Vashem Holocaust Museum in Tel Aviv, tells the story of one of the most dramatic pages in history.
The most tragic part of the museum - the Children's Memorial - was built in memory of 1.5 million children who were murdered in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You will enter – and you will find yourself in total darkness.
The stars are shining.
And the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they perished.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Improve your health
Israel’s three main spa resorts are located on the Mediterranean, Red and Dead Sea coasts.
Each of them offers swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
It is interesting that in the Red Sea you can swim even in the winter months, because the water temperature in it does not fall below 21 degrees Celsius and the air warms up to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer, and people bathe in it all year round.
The Dead Sea, by the way, is the strangest sea in the world, located at the lowest land point of the planet - at a level of 417 m below sea level.
The azure water in it is a saturated salt solution that easily keeps on the surface even people who can not swim.
The surrounding landscape is unrealistically beautiful.
Come here to undergo treatment using salt water - brine, and healing mud, which can treat health problems with dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes, to cure cramped nerves.
Touch the Mysterious Past
It is protected by the ancient part of Tel Aviv - the town of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through them passed the famous sea route connecting Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
Mentions of this city are found in the oldest Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it is the place where Noah built his ark and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom they lived a long and happy life together.
Tourists really love to wander through narrow streets, named after the zodiac signs.
It is said that if you press against the walls in the alley of "your" sign, happiness will favor you.
In Jaffa, you may meet newlyweds who come here from all over Israel and even from other countries to be photographed.
And in Caesarea - in the city of King Herod - you can walk through the Roman theater and "conquer" the fortress of the crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the capital of Judea and the seat of Roman prosecutors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully reconstructed theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Tourists, in a word.
If you are going to Israel, you do not have to worry about your imperfect English: in this country about 30% of the population speak Russian.
It is better to take money with you not in euros, but in dollars, which you can easily exchange for shekels (now 1 dollar is about 3.8 shekels).
There are mainly buses, but Jerusalem has a high-speed tram and Haifa is the only metro line in the country with six stations that connects the lower city with the upper one.
It is basically an underground cable car.
Travelling by all types of public transport costs 6 shekels, for which you can drive for 1.5 hours with a changeover.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated on the Sabbath.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, work stops at markets, shops and public transport.
And on Sunday morning, the work week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and hotels you will get only kosher food: except for pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes containing combinations of milk and meat.
They offer a large selection of lamb and beef dishes, soups and desserts, prepared from coconut milk, traditional Jewish porridge hummus, various kinds of sauces, minced chickpeas balls - falafel, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
