While lawmakers and human rights defenders are still debating a law on compulsory language exams, fraudsters have already emerged in the country selling “fake” certificates.
Every year, 13 million foreign workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn enough money to support families at home.
On December 1, the law came into force, according to which every working migrant will be obliged to pass the exam of knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the services, housing and utilities, lifestyle and retail sectors.
However, FMS promises that over time, the relevant tests will be mandatory for all visitors.
However, the exams will consist not only of language skills, but also of Russian history and the foundations of law.
Proficiency in the language will also be required to obtain and renew a work permit.
The exception applies only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
This law does not apply even to people who successfully managed to achieve attestation and obtain an academic diploma until the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Benefit, condemnation and protection of rights
The network of test sites will operate under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute of the Russian Language, the University of Friendship between Nations, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants can take exams in all cities; more than 160 such centers are already open in Russia.
The initiative to support the introduction of testing was also supported by deputies of the State Duma and FMS (Federal Migration Services).
But before the law came into force, human rights defenders were able to ask the press many times: and what will it actually bring?
What will change the obligation to know the language for the Russians and for the visitors themselves?
