Many people today talk about the protection of the rights of migrant workers, explains Chairman of the Board of FMS of Russia in Tajikistan Viktor Sebelev.
The protection of their rights should begin before they leave.
Only a system of organized recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Problems arise with emigrants without a profession, without education, who do not know the language and do not have a medical examination.
Without knowledge of the language, Sebelev says, the future migrant is doomed to clashes with dishonest people who, under the pretext of helping him, will provide a "ticket" to terrible, tight hostels, in which he and dozens of others, like himself, will suffer for months without food and documents and work for 12 to 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrant workers.
“They promise them one thing in their homeland, but when they arrive, they cheat them, they confiscate their passports, they don’t pay the promised wages,” said Tolib Sharipov, head of the General Directorate of Labour Migration in Tajikistan.
Don't broadcast!
Especially since many citizens of Central Asian republics who intend to go to work in Russia recognize that they not only do not know the language of the country they want to enter, but do not even have experience with the work.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as rather their misfortune: very few Turkmens, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to get at least a reasonable basic education.
After all, their families also need something to feed their children, not to mention the fact that they need to be properly dressed, dressed and equipped for school.
As children reach a productive age, they must go to work at the first opportunity.
Without knowledge of the language, it is difficult - they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
It is true that, with regard to the Language Examination Act, human rights defenders point to one important thing.
The tests will only be carried out on migrants who have legal status.
If they don't have it, they won't take the exams or get any other official job.
Meanwhile, the majority of migrant workers still live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome, or Unauthorized Entry Banned"
Many of the incoming workers claim that getting an official status in our country is not easy.
The reason - bureaucratic obstacles and all those language difficulties.
Legalization, in addition, costs money: from 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
But fake registration can be obtained quickly and only one and a half thousand.
Employees of the Russian police know that we basically have fake documents, without registration, and this leads to cases of blackmail.
"They demand a hundred, two for cigarettes, tea," Tajikistani citizen Umed Chushkadamov told reporters.
"Come on, don't be greedy, buy yourself a painting"
On the first day of the language law, it was found that not only the registration documents of migrants are fake.
FMS employees have already confiscated several false certificates for passing the language exam.
Forged documents are printed on an ordinary color printer.
Of course, they did not get to the new owners for free: each of the migrants, hoping to ease the problem of passing the tests, paid for this document seven thousand rubles.
This is two and a half times the amount of the official test: it will cost migrant workers three thousand rubles.
The main task of the near future is to secure the system against corruption, so that workers can not simply buy documents, government officials and human rights defenders agree.
For the time being, government authorities can promise foreign workers who failed the tests for the first time the time needed to complete the Russian language basics course.
Visitors who do not speak Russian are expected to work in areas where active interaction with people is not required.
