The Ministry of Internal Affairs of Russia proposes to tighten the law in relation to the owners of civilian weapons.
It is the reaction of government authorities to recent events: the stimulus was the cases of shootings at weddings that went without victims, and the massacre prepared by Moscow lawyer Dimitri Vinogradov, which resulted in the deaths of seven people.
Police want to ban the carrying of dangerous weapons in public places and increase the age from which you can get a license to carry weapons - from 18 to 21 years.
This idea is supported by the head of the Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption Irina Jarovaya, who promised that changes to the law on weapons will be submitted to the State Duma in the near future.
Not everyone is satisfied with the fact that the Russian state authorities are trying to cope with the problem by "tightening the screws".
An open letter appeared on the network, the authors of which - representatives of various social shooting organizations - demanded the rejection of the "nonsensical tightening" of the law.
The percentage of hooliganism with registered weapons is minimal, said Vasily Lesnikov, a lawyer and criminalist, in an interview with the Russian BBC.
According to the Ministry of the Interior statistics, 142 offences involving firearms registered by the Ministry of the Interior were committed in the six months of 2012, while a total of 1168 thousand offences were committed in the same period.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that the tightening of the legislation in the field of civil weapons will not force the perpetrator to switch to the "black" market.
According to them, at present, any weapon can be found in Moscow at a low price.
Currently, the Ministry of the Interior says that the situation with the proliferation of illegal weapons is under control.
