In the United States, workers of fast food and supermarkets
A quarter of all U.S. teens will work at McDonald’s.
In recent days, there has been a wave of protests in America against low wages in Walmart hypermarkets and in restaurants of popular fast food chains, such as "McDonald", "Burger King", "Taco Bell", "Wendy's" and "Kentucky Fried Chicken".
So far, no one can predict whether this wave will turn into the ninth wave, or whether it is destined to soon disappear.
The whole action is supported by trade unions and a number of left-wing social organizations.
In addition to raising the modest salaries that regular workers in Walmart and in fast food systems receive, the goal of the protest organizers is to create them in their trade union organizations.
Currently, this economic sector is virtually untouched by the trade union movement.
46 cents a year?
The action began last week after Thanksgiving, the so-called "Black Friday", when an orgy of cheap sales hit America, captivated millions of residents, and in some cases was accompanied by brawls.
On this day, some employees of Walmart, which employs 2.2 million people worldwide, left their workplaces and demonstrated together with trade unions and left-wing activists of multinational retail chains whose goods are intended for lower- and middle-class people.
Walmart sells everything from diapers to hunting rifles and car batteries to vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
Products in its stores are on average 8% to 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
That’s why many low-wage employees in Walmart stores shop only at work.
The availability and range of products have made Walmart one of the largest companies in America.
According to critics, Walmart can afford to sell goods so cheaply, partly because it pays its employees little.
They also complain about poor working conditions, such as the lack of automatic trolleys or hand scanners.
Protesters on Black Friday demanded a pay rise and complained that the company’s health insurance costs rose sharply from $30 to $100 a month.
A typical Walmart employee gets $9.5 an hour, but that doesn’t match the cost, employees say.
Researchers at the University of California, Berkeley, say that if Walmart raises the average salary to $12 an hour, it will cost the company $3.2 billion a year.
That’s an average of 1.1% more than the company spends on salaries now.
If Walmart shifts the wage increase fully to consumers, each visit to the store will cost just 46 cents more.
In a year, customers spend about $12.39 more than they do today.
Walmart advocates point out that the protest took place in only nine countries and should not cause virtually any harm to society.
"Black Friday" in the company's stores lasted from 8 p.m. on Thursday to midnight the following day, and during that time Walmart was selling about 5,000 items per second.
In total, its cash registers carried out nearly 100 million transactions on Black Friday.
In an interview with the left-wing Huffington Post, Dan Fogelman said that a total of “less than five” Walmart employees had left their jobs and that the protest was “another media sensation” organized by unions.
"Unoccupied cash register!"
The protests continued this week in New York, where their goal was not Walmart department stores (they in the mentioned progressive city are not very popular, and therefore are almost not there), but "McDonald" and other cheap restaurants.
McDonald says he sells billions of servings, and then he doesn't even pay you sick pay, and he doesn't pay you properly for your honest work!
Jumaane Williams, New York City Council Member
Currently, the minimum wage for work in accordance with federal laws and regulations of the state of New York is $7.25 per hour.
Fast food restaurants are gradually raising this wage, but only slightly, and on average their regular workers in New York receive $8.90 per hour.
No one in this expensive city has a lower salary.
I don't understand how you can exist in New York for that kind of money.
Almost a quarter of American teenagers who work behind the desk after school part-time and live with their parents will be employed by McDonald’s.
Few people see this as their main source of livelihood or plan to stay there for a long time.
At present, I constantly meet in an interview with McDonald's workers who complain that they have to live on this money and sometimes even feed their children.
On the other hand, there is a comment on the Wall Street Journal forum, the author of which notes that it is irresponsible to have children if you do not know how to feed them.
Protesters, who began at 6:30 a.m. on Thursday morning at McDonald’s on 40th Street and Madison Avenue, demanded that cashiers and cooks at fast food businesses start receiving at least $15 an hour, more than double their current minimum wage.
They also demanded that trade unions be established in the field of fast food.
U.S. law prohibits the administration from preventing the creation of trade union organizations and punishing trade union activists with bullying and dismissal.
On the other hand, administration rarely makes their lives easier.
However, the introduction of a trade union in fast food companies is also difficult for objective reasons.
One of the main reasons is the extremely high fluctuation of employees.
Disagreement
On this day, there were also loud protests in a number of other cheap restaurants in Manhattan.
