- Surely it can not be considered an omnivore - the question of privacy arises, because we do not always want to inform others in our surroundings about their activities and intentions.
In fact, all types of interactions with computers are good, but in their own environment.
For example, for the operation of devices in public places, we had a project in which we thought about gestures, but not about swollen ones, just about such sluggish, short ones.
The gesture would not be filmed with a camera, but with a bracelet that would monitor the movements of bones and muscles.
So far, it is large, but theoretically it can be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
In general, however, the future has a mixed type of control, such as gesture + voice.
- How's that?
- How do you ask me to give you this can of lemonade, for example?
You say it and you show it at the same time.
- I usually just talk.
- Oh, it's gonna be very difficult to tell.
- So you want to get users to adapt to what the machine can or cannot do at a given moment?
- It's not necessary at all, but it's mutual rapprochement.
I think that in the near future we will have to work primarily on the development of new types of sensors that can more accurately detect human reactions.
These can be, for example, laser sensors that provide a fairly good depth resolution, this is very important.
- If you need to talk about your work with Xbox Kinect sensors, what are your requirements for modern cameras?
Isn't there enough resolution, depth, or something else today?
- Basically, the current generation - this is what we can reflect on in our work on three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, it would be good to get 8 megapixels at 1000 f/s.
But it’s not just about the megapixels themselves, but as a matrix and depth.
At the same time, all current technologies are insufficient for us - this assigns work to designers of algorithms.
So we have to keep in mind not only the resolution in the X and Y axes, but also Z.
So speed is also very important, the number of frames per second.
Human movement is quite dynamic, and current data flows of 30 frames per second are, frankly, a little bit, especially for gestures.
Stephen Betishes from our lab in Redmond made a touch sensor with an adjustable processing delay of 1 to 100 ms, with current, mass-produced sensors closer to the second value (60-100 ms).
Not everyone understands the extent to which this affects human interaction with the machine.
For me, the equivalent of such a device would be very useful at work, I just do not need so many touches, but I need some extra images per second.
And there's no need to increase the number of cameras?
- Three "cameras" are now used in the Kinect system, one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the other - a receiver of the reflected signal.
And the third camera - this is actually a regular sensor of the visible band.
It is not used to determine the depth of the object.
More cameras could potentially solve the problem...
Or worsen it, because it would increase the required volume of calculations.
It would be nice to create a flexible analog Kinect system, play with the curvature of the location of the cameras and see how it will help in determining the three-dimensional position.
As far as I can remember, Microsoft (unlike Google) did not publicly present its glasses.
Don’t you think that when it comes to the daily use of augmented reality technology using special glasses, this is one of the most promising platforms?
- Of course, walking around and constantly holding the smatphone in the raised hands is not very comfortable, but I think the strongest option would be a "portable" form of reality expansion, where it would be possible to switch from glasses to a smartphone, a projection display and then around the clock based on the cloud platform.
