- Imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is available not only to Tony Stark in "Iron Man", but also to the ordinary mortal.
There is one problem that critics often point out: there is no touch response!
Hands can't feel anything!
What are your group’s responses to this challenge?
In my lectures I often say that augmented reality is the seventh consecutive breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the addition of tactile sensations could easily become the eighth breakthrough.
So far, one of the interesting tricks is used - the use of the second hand as a certain kind of background for imaging.
Excellent way to record compression!
But there are also technologies that are really aimed at adding tactility to these "pictures in the air" - for example, the interference of several directional ultrasound beams at a defined point where the finger is located, it causes a tactile sensation, but it is still very weak - as if you were blowing on the abdomen of your fingers.
There is also a wrist bracelet that affects the nerve endings in the fingers - also a promising direction.
- Have you tried to fool the brain?
To think that he feels what it seems he should feel at the moment when he sees something?
- That's a good idea. We haven't tried that yet.
Here is another challenge that will be fought for for a long time - how to get a person who is physically in a very cramped space to believe that he is walking in an open, practically infinite space - we are also working on the concept of cross-country tracks (not at all like in clubs), moving platforms and also huge balls.
If brain deception becomes a goal, then work is for many years to come.
That’s what makes virtual reality work so appealing to researchers — a lot of things are in their infancy.
