We have put all this together, and although the inspection is not yet completed, we have seen very interesting differences - in general terms, the legislation in our country is perhaps even "stricter and more perfect", but the practice itself is better in Germany in some parameters.
It is therefore confirmed that it is not enough to create more and more precise rules, but it is necessary to focus on the application of law itself.
What can this project really help you with, what does it mean for you?
It is this kind of joint control that could help us stop making efforts to clarify laws, reduce and improve limits when it does not have such a positive impact.
Economy means getting the right thing at a reasonable (but not always the lowest) price in order to exclude enrichment and possibly criminal conduct.
But by lowering the procurement limit, we don’t necessarily have to achieve that.
Maybe the system will get so full of "paper" that those who want to look for holes in the system will draw from it much easier than if the limit remained higher.
You are talking about domestic problems with the transposition of legislation on public procurement into practice.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is it similar to ours, or is it different?
As far as the authorities are concerned, just as the SAO operates there, the Bundesrevisionshof, which is organized like us, also has a college, only formed in a slightly different way, but in principle both authorities act in a similar way.
The powers are also somewhat similar, but the fact that Germany has a federal arrangement means that it has these courts of account at the level of the individual federal states - in this the system differs a little from ours.
The BRH can only control the federal money represented by state funds.
Public funds, which are administered by our regions and municipalities, are controlled there from the level of federal accounting courts.
As far as legislation is concerned, it is easier than ours.
In general, I would not like to compare this without specific data, but in some respects Germany is often referred to as a model, but it cannot be said that it is better in all respects.
Is it because they have better controllers?
Certainly not, but again, I don't like that kind of comparison.
But it must be said that even the countries that we consider to be a model face a number of problems.
Otherwise, it wouldn't be any good for them to work with our office, would it?
As for domestic legislation, what did the amendment to the Public Procurement Act mean for your office, do its effects already manifest themselves?
Since the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it is not yet manifested in our control actions.
Since we do ex-post checks, it is necessary to count on a certain delay.
We are only seeing this so far in the process of preparing future controls - we have launched our new tool "detection of risks of inefficiency", through which we have passed almost 14,000 public contracts, and we have analysed them - there, of course, these changes will be reflected, because the limits will change, the conditions of some types of tendering will be adjusted, and so on.
Do you consider the approval of this law to be a benefit or an additional burden on the system of bureaucracy?
I think that this law is definitely a step in the right direction, and I hope that this will be confirmed.
The problem that may arise here is that these rules will be "stricted" and will not be able to be observed.
For the functioning of the previous rules, the audited persons are obliged by the provider (for example, in the case of regional operational programmes, by the regional council) to ensure that any failure to comply with the law on public procurement constitutes a breach of budgetary discipline.
Is it worth it to tighten the law in this way?
I don't think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse it, and not punish those who commit a formal error that does not affect decision-making.
Such a system will only put more pressure on bureaucracy.
So how do we get out of this?
Let's see where the road doesn't lead.
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the ODS would not bother entrepreneurs with checks on the so-called "swartz system" - and what does that mean?
Is the blackout system banned or allowed?
After all, the law must be somehow set up, and if it forbids anything, then the Prime Minister cannot prevent the activities of the Office, which is obliged to go to control and enforce its duties.
He can say, "We'll change the law and allow it," but he can't say we'll do nothing.
There are fairly strict rules in the Public Procurement Act on how to formally implement what is right to protect public competition.
But on the other hand, it is tragic when an interested party with the best offer is excluded only for formal shortcomings.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct - this is what we think is missing.
