Poland and space.
Last week, at a meeting of European Space Agency Ministers, Poland was admitted as the 20th member of the European Space Agency, as the second country from the countries of the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland started close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and over the following years participated in a number of projects of the Agency.
However, Poland’s journey to space began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already engaged in spaceflights before World War II; but they did not always meet with understanding.
I would like to recall, for example, A. Sternfeld’s lecture at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, which on December 6, 1933 presented ideas from his pioneering work, Entry into Cosmonautics.
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the audience cold, and after years Sternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
Sternfeld was awarded the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize in 1934 for his Entry into Space in France.
The mentioned doctor Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great propagator of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He has published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and has written a number of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-renowned propagandist of cosmonautics, and his contribution was also appreciated by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the moon was named after him.
Already in 1925, a railway dredge was built in Poland, which was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the proposal is not known and the details of the project are not known.
It is not even clear whether the missile should have been used to start the dredge or to brake it.
Information about this drezina is known only from the period press.
Since 1933, the Polish artillery began to be used with rocket missiles.
The research was provided by the Armament Technology Cell in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfek and Prof. Gustav Mokrzycki.
From the preserved materials, it is clear that the research has reached the stage of practical tests.
However, with the arrival of German troops, the research was interrupted.
In 1937, the design of the photoelectric fighter missile, designed by engineer Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski, appeared in the professional press, and in the following year, the work Raketa - an air torpedo and an aerial bomb by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki was published.
Both projects were designed for the military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Temczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was involved in all projects of military use of missile technology, which coordinated all the work.
The Committee was established in 1937, but after two years of activity its activity ended the beginning of the war.
After the war, other works devoted to space exploration appeared in the Polish press thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, the company is mentioned in the November issue of the 1954 issue of the journal Problemy, which contains four more comprehensive articles on astronautics.
In one of them, from Prof. M. Subotowicz, it is proposed to create a company that will deal with cosmonautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were already underway, and it was clear that space research was a promising field.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) has been striving to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951) and in the autumn, the PTA became a full member.
And the following year, the first chairman of the PTA Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959) became the vice-chairman of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been instrumental in the development of the highly successful Meteorological Missile RM (Meteorological Missile), which became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with an access of 1800 meters was about 80 cm long and weighed less than 5 kg.
Later, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959, flight tests of the two-stage RM-2 rocket were launched in the Bled Desert.
The rocket was 1.4 meters long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
The next development type was supposed to be capable of real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket was supposed to have a range of up to 14.5 km and its task was to monitor the altitude wind.
However, in 1962, further development was suspended.
The successor to the first RM-type rocket was the Meteor-1 rocket developed from 1962 to 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (designated Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed in the size of the space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had 0.4 litres of space, the Meteor-1B had 0.34 litres, and the Meteor-1C had 0.62 litres.
The maximum access for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Aeronautical Institute developed the Meteor-2 rocket, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had a launch weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
Poland's accession to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of the COSPAR National Committee two years later.
Poland was also involved in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites as part of the Intercosmos program, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remko.
Repealing the Public Works Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court overturned the Public Works Act.
The resolution sparked a lively debate in public.
It will certainly be interesting to look at the issue from a broader perspective.
Liberally oriented economic systems in the EU as well as in the globalized world are based on the principle of more, unregulated competition.
In its effect, this means that the individual economic units, the national economic systems, are in permanent conflict with each other.
The reason is the principle of free trade and the free, unrestricted movement of private capital, together with unbridled financial speculation.
Due to the significant differences in the price of labour, (wages) there is a price tension.
By this term it is necessary to understand the situation when a producer tries to withstand competition by importing cheap goods by "cheating up" the price of a competitor in order to take on a larger market share and thereby increase its own profits.
On a mass scale, this means for most entrepreneurs either to transfer production abroad, or to buy cheaply there, or to disappear.The result is high unemployment in countries where labor prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility, and therefore no responsibility for the resulting unemployment, the social expenditures of the state necessarily increase.
The whole situation is enhanced by the complete reluctance of the masters of entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thereby compensate for the economic and social damage they caused in the pursuit of profit.
The situation is so well known that it is not necessary to provide specific statistics.
The ruthless practices of private capital create a situation in individual economies where national governments are forced to enter into competition with each other in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments are giving private capital a chance to its own population, regardless of social decline.
This is mainly reflected in the changes to the laws in force.
The aim is to force its own population to adopt a price dictate of private capital, especially in the field of wages.
This is done, on the one hand, by a system of economic coercion in the event of long-term unemployment, on the other, by restricting the rights of workers in the field of labour law.
The result is increasing poverty, coupled with an increase in the gap between the rich and the poor.
There have been public food dispensaries for the poor in Germany for many years, who cannot feed on their own work.
The number of these people is already in the millions.
In the context of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, it is quite common for properly employed people to receive such wages that the state has to pay them to an existential minimum.
Such a scandal was published even in the case of auxiliary employees of the Federal Assembly.
The austerity measures of virtually all the southern EU countries undoubtedly lead to the same situation where people under the pressure of a catastrophic decline in the social level are forced either to emigrate as they were in the 19th century, or to live at starvation wages on the margins of society in the hope that private investment capital may one day enter the country.
But the question is where does it come from?
If it is from other EU countries, then poverty will move from one country to another, or it will not come at all, because the Chinese, Indians, Brazilians, or Turks, Moroccans, Egyptians, or Africans are still working for a fraction of the European wage.
This applies to all of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media infuriately argue that the state cannot participate capitally in its own economy, that a controlled economy leads to an economic catastrophe.
Private capital stubbornly insists that the state must not intervene in the economy by directing interventions.
Then it is necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence, now it actually manages politics and thus the whole state in its own egoistic sense.
Here is a clear answer that yes.
The evidence is the existence of a practically omnipotent and ubiquitous lobby in all states.
The result is a desperate situation manifesting itself in the field of corruption, providing mutual benefits, legislation where practically everything is criminal, but nothing is criminal.
In Germany, the situation is such that state ministries for lack of funds order the drafting of laws to private law firms, which are often associated with industry.
These bills are then approved in the Bundestag.
All power in this way does not come from the people, as Western-style constitutions say, but from financially strong groups preferring their own interests.
It is clear that liberally oriented democracies are now quickly getting into a situation as Appianos describes it in his Crisis of the Roman Republic under Caesar and Pompey: “The state has long been in complete disintegration and the authorities have been occupied by violence.
For bribes, for unlawful gain of favor, and with the help of stones or swords.
Bribery and corruption were rampant without any hindrance, and the people went to the elections with a pre-sold vote" ..."characteristic people did not run for office at all, so one day as a result of this breakdown was to stand eight months without consuls." .."It began to talk about the fact that the only cure in a bad situation is self-government, and that a man needs to be elected."
As in antiquity, modern society is based on a reckless preference for self-interest, regardless of the social interest.
Private capital is no longer, by its very nature, capable of understanding and applying the whole-society benefit.
The result is now, as at the time, an unprecedented decadence of elites without any deeper reform efforts.
We must therefore look for the causality of the rise of fascist and communist regimes in the ruthless liberalization of the economic systems of the 19th and 20th centuries.
In the current situation, the demise of these systems in favor of a liberal democracy can be considered a certain break with the expectation of the next round.
Particularly disastrous is the fact that the current elites completely ignore in the future the possible hundreds of thousands of lives lost, humanitarian and social catastrophes that we are already witnessing together with crimes against humanity, as we know them from old and new history.
Repealing the Public Works Act is not a solution, at least not a permanent one.
Under the pressure of competition at both international and internal European level, the government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to further reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is systemic.
The solution is targeted political and social reforms that will strengthen the state's capital participation in the economy, strengthen the influence of citizens on the government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
