Argo: When It's Worst, Call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of Islamist students seized the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the ousted Shah Mohammed Reza P<0xC3><0xA1>hlavi, who fled to the United States after the revolution, which had been the patron of his regime for several decades.
For the US administration, the situation did not offer a positive outcome - she could not afford to throw a shah overboard, because it would fundamentally jeopardize the trust of allies in other countries.
But the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution resulted in the establishment of a theocratic regime, was not able to achieve.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was later deepened by the fiasco of the attempt to free the hostages by force.
The incarcerated diplomats were eventually released after 444 days, after negotiations were brokered by the Algerian government.
Their fate at home has sparked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment.
Debacle in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
Director Ben Affleck's film Argo chronicles an episode of the story that brought America a small victory.
Just before the embassy was occupied, six employees fled.
After difficult peripeti, they ended up in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, helped by an extravagant cover story - they went on Canadian passports as members of the film staff, who in the country inspected the locations for filming sci-fi big films.
Combination of genres
The plan, devised by Tony Mendez, an expert on “exfiltration,” also required Hollywood’s cooperation.
To make the legend credible, a film project was written in specialized magazines, press conferences were held, a fictional production company had a real office.
The details of the operation have been kept secret for a long time, the film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a strange combination of multiple genres.
On the one hand, a realistically conceived political thriller, at the same time the so-called "caper movie", a story of a successful piece, a trick - an example can be the series of Danny's partners.
In the film, moods alternate - on the one hand, documentary sequences from Tehran (in the subtitle sequence, iconic period photographs of events are shown, as well as the way in which the same situations were presented in the film - there are no big differences in this).
On the other hand, lighter passages from Hollywood, reconciled with irony and a slight exaggeration.
And then there's scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions-- men in suits discussing the situation at the negotiating tables, in the corridors of the office, on the phone...
Ben Affleck managed to relaunch his career in a remarkable way.
The ridiculed actor became a respected director and his acting ceased to be the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film, after the dark crime film Gone Baby Gone (2007) and the thriller City (2010).
It is also Affleck's first film not to feature in the director's hometown of Boston.
At the same time, the feeling for the atmosphere of the place was among the characteristics that raised the director's older films above the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck also shows it in Arg, where Tehran "plays" Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place in the streets, reconstructing real events - the opening sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive in its clarity, which at the same time mediates the emotions of confusion and unpredictability that occur when history suddenly moves somewhere.
A similar effect is achieved by Affleck and his collaborators in fictional scenes (a fake staff at a Tehran bazaar).
Too many stories in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story told does not actually offer much in the film sense of tense scenes.
He works quite successfully with it, sometimes he comes up with something to reality - there everything is not so elegant (a scene in which the impending crisis at Tehran airport turns off the phone call in America and the chase after the runway seems quite drawn by the hair).
The weakness of Arga, however, is the distraction resulting from the need to show too many stories in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in the roles of Hollywood collaborators, but their characters would deserve more space and they are not the only ones in the film.
Affleck’s film somewhat loses its dramatic thrust, it is a film that can be watched with moderate interest, appreciate the realization and retro style evoking the thrillers of the 70s.
But it's hard to pull.
As a reminder of one so far living history in a certain way, and proof of how exaggerated the notions of all-powerful and all-knowing secret services are, it is enough.
