MVRDV architects are proof that real adventures don’t just happen in the head – for example, Spijkenisse and the recently built Mountain of Books – 2 photos
"The building looks cheerful, futuristic, and finally there's something interesting to see again," says Lisette Verhaig, who walks around on the side of the road.
Stefan Spermon, an IT technician at a nearby big business, says, "Of course, the house is nice."
I wonder why we still need a library.
They all have internet, iPads and e-books.
Nobody goes to any of these old-style libraries voluntarily anymore, right?
Spijkenisse, a settlement in the immediate vicinity of Rotterdam without its own job opportunities, which are not even worth a visit, holds a special record.
With a population of 80,000, this municipality has the lowest level of education in the Netherlands.
To resolve this stupid situation, a few years ago a decision was made to contribute to general education and to build seven beautifully painted reinforced concrete miniatures of fictitious bridges depicted on euro banknotes.
However, the success of the educational offensive was not dizzying.
And so the city councillors realized that there was only one way to become masters of statistics: we must have a library!
Winy Maas of the MVRDV Rotterdam architectural studio, master of insanely daring column charts and the maker of funny, often even cynical constructions, accepted the matter with the usual calmness and appeared at a competition meeting in 2003 with five books under his arm and a grin on his face.
And while the commission looked around in amazement and shrugged, the insolent Maas threw his gifts at himself according to size, and ended his activist-motivated speech with the words "Dear Town Township!"
So this is my proposal for the Mountain of Books at Spijkenisse, the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the mountain was completed for 30 million euros.
It is part of a revitalization project, which also includes an underground parking lot, a supermarket, a post office and several adjacent residential and terraced houses with a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, Mountain of Books was awarded the second place "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project is also nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Small-town grey, which could not yet offer more than a postmodern pedestrian zone and an unusually ugly town hall, behind whose white facade you would rather expect a dairy, is richer with a bit of contemporary architecture.
Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in the history of its existence.
The Long Road to the Book
First impression: a reader's eldorado under the hatch for cheese.
Although there is an elevator through the massif of the mountain, you will discover real spatial and reader’s passions only when you cross the topography on foot.
On all sides, the glazed interior is bright and clear, the floor of the burnt cabrine and the elegant street lanterns clearly express the atmosphere of the public square.
The urban environment is perfect.
You see park benches, a dog and boys and girls playing football.
And books, books, books everywhere.
“Normally there are shelves with books along the facade and in the middle is a large dark space that is mostly uncomfortable and impersonal,” says Winy Maas.
We put the classic spatial configuration upside down and pushed the space for the reader from the inside out.
The interior of the Mountain of Books is cleverly used: in the center there are offices, an Internet library, a chess club, an ecological center and a headquarters of home technology.
A special delight are black bookshelves, which are once a wall cladding, once a window sill and sometimes a railing of the stairs.
Appearance, structure and smell are foreign.
Even architects and civil engineers have vowed to shake their heads over the unknown building material.
“We wanted to work here with recycled materials,” says Joop Trouborst, project manager at Spijkenisse, when asked by Standard magazine.
So one day, at a Frisian farm, we came across a suitable waste product from agriculture.
For many years, in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands, a millimeter fleece made of synthetic material has been used as a base under the roots.
It is cheap and time efficient.
Thin textiles last one, two seasons and then are ripe for disposal in bulky waste.
For the library, the fleece - for the first time in such quantity - was pressed onto boards four centimeters thick.
With the action of heat and pressure, the so-called Landbouwplastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous and load-bearing material that smells a bit like a new car and a bit like sports shoes.
After 105 steps you will reach the top.
At the end of the nearly 500-metre journey, you will be rewarded with a fantastic view of the city, as well as Dutch croquettes and figs in pots.
They care about the atmosphere, but mainly about the correct humidity of the air in the mountains of literature.
Gifts for a new soul
“You probably wouldn’t believe it, but this house, despite its many glass surfaces, is a showcase project in terms of ecology,” says Trouborst.
It is heated and cooled by the heat of the earth.
Although the Mountain of Books stands under a glass lid, the sun shines inside only briefly, even on sunny days.
Wide glued wooden trusses, standing perpendicular to the glazed facade, serve as a shading and capture a large part of the sun's radiation.
The climate in the room is very pleasant.
The rest can be done with fully automatic roller shutters.
Stefan Spermon, an initial skeptic from the IT industry, has already visited the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
And also the teacher of traditional Chinese medicine Cynthia Bogarde, who Boekenberg even calls the "long-awaited soul" Spijkenisse.
The reason: every resident of the city was invited to the opening a few weeks ago to donate one book from his personal fund.
First, the optical gaps were to be filled in the not yet fully equipped library, which currently has 70,000 pieces.
The concept has proven itself.
The shelves are full.
“There is nothing worse than a half-empty library,” says architect Winy Maas.
"I think that thanks to our invitation, every resident now has a certain relationship to the new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it was just an ornament.
Thus, the MVRDV succeeded in the royal discipline, which in professional jargon is called the formation of identity.
Spijkenisse wrote the history of literature.
No matter how young or uneducated he is.
This is the starting point for identity.
