But some scientists and experts on child development are increasingly coming up with praise for boredom.
They say that it is good for us (and our children) to get bored sometimes.
It forces the brain to go in interesting directions, which can encourage creativity.
And since most of us are constantly connected to a screen these days, we have no chance to enjoy boredom.
Should we encourage boredom?
Oh, yeah.
Oh, no.
But I'll get back to that.
First of all, like many people, I assumed that boredom is a relatively new phenomenon, which occurred with the advent of more free time.
But as Peter Toohey, a professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada, says, he is the author of Boredom: A Lively History (Yale University Press, 2011).
"In fact, boredom has a long history," he said.
On the walls of Pompeii was found a Latin inscription about boredom, dating from the first century AD.
And then there's the question of how we define boredom.
The problem is that it has been defined and discussed in many different ways, said John D. Eastwood, professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After looking at the research literature and presenting the idea to the target group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as an experience "I wanted to do something that would satisfy me, but I was not able to do it."
Boredom differs from apathy in that a person is not involved in anything, but would like to be.
He says there's no compulsion to do anything about apathy.
He says that the core of boredom is "the disruption of the process of attention, associated with a bad mood and a feeling of slow passing time."
Boredom can be a lot like depression.
But Professor Eastwood said that while they can have a relationship with each other, bored people tend to see the problem as the environment or the world, while people who are depressed see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we’re bored when we’re just having trouble concentrating.
In their study, The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention, published in Perspectives on Psychological Science in September, Professor Eastwood and colleagues pointed to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape of a person reading an article from the journal.
Some groups heard the loud, unrelated television program in the next room, others heard it so quietly that they barely noticed it, while the third group did not hear it at all.
Those who heard the TV program silently reported more boredom than the other two groups — they had trouble concentrating, but they weren’t sure why, and attributed those troubles to boredom.
When you’re trying to focus on a difficult or engaging task, distraction can lead to boredom, said Mark J. Fenske, a professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the study’s authors.
On the other hand, when you’re doing something boring, “like finding the wrong parts on the factory line, distracting music can help you not get bored.”
In fact, he said, we now know that twisting and frowning, often seen as a sign of boredom, can actually help fight boredom and keep people physically alert.
