On the other hand, many philosophers and writers have debated the connection between boredom and creativity, said Professor Vodanovich, who has studied the problem for more than two decades.
"Luck is a way of the brain to tell you that you should do something else," said Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at NYU.
But the brain doesn’t always know the best thing you should do.
If you get bored and use this energy to play guitar and cook, it will make you happy.
However, if you watch TV, it will make you happy only for a while, not for a long time.
So if your child gets bored and you give him an iPad, he won’t get bored anymore, but he won’t learn how to have fun on his own or drive on his own, Professor Fenske said.
And "this separate procedure is transferred from one situation to another," the professor said.
Your child will not only learn how to entertain himself, but will gain more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we really want to celebrate boredom.
