"The daily wage of miners here is very high. For example, for collecting coffee, 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) are paid per day and the salary for fourteen days is two million rupees (167 euros), "explains the carrier, who previously worked on the tourist island of Bali as a bricklayer.
There was his salary of 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) per day and the work was not so heavy, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a serious reason that is as convincing in Indonesia as sulfur: "I married a young girl from Bali who is Hindu, and I took her to Converva."
Anto has asthma, he's having trouble breathing, he's always coughing and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto risks his life three times a day in the Kawah Ijen volcano, whose sulfur has already begun to levy its toll on him, despite his face being protected by a special mask and glasses.
He's got asthma, he's having a bad breath, he's still coughing, and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases that escape from the volcano.
This is the price you have to pay to achieve your dream.
“I’m going to work for two more years because I want to open a business or study Spanish or French,” he said.
This sympathetic and intelligent young man haunted by fate could be a tour guide, waiter or receptionist in a hotel, and instead do the work of a carrier.
She shares a dirty wooden hut with other carriers and gets up every day at two in the morning, because the sulfur does not cease to fade at night, and its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the dark.
Despite the surrounding darkness, Anto flies into the crater and lights his way with a small flashlight attached to his helmet, which he bought for his own money.
About 400 carriers carry sulphur baskets from the bottom of the crater on their shoulders
Although the company has high incomes, sulphur mining has not been mechanized, nor does it provide any equipment to carriers working on their own and with such effort.
In fact, they don’t even get a share of 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) from the photography surcharge, which, along with a 15,000 rupee (1.2 euros) ticket, nature park guards collect from tourists who come to take pictures of the volcano and its human mules.
“This job is for cattle, not people,” Madrusin, a 42-year-old carrier who has been working at Kawah Ion for only three decades, has objected since he left school.
He can lift up to 110 kilos and assures us that he will last as long as he can, because he needs money to educate his three sons between the ages of 18 and 10.
I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano has been my whole life
Although sulfur burns the throat and bites in the eyes, when the wind unexpectedly turns and catches the miners in the dense fumes that come out of the volcano, the miners are so claiming that none of them complains that they suffer from serious illnesses... but this is evident from their frequent respiratory problems, arthritis and pain of the shoulders.
Unainik, who balances his basket on his back, can only load 50 kilos at the age of 53.
Every day, he and his colleagues mine 15 tons of sulfur in the volcano, which is then transported by three trucks by a steep path between the thicket to a warehouse in Tamansari, 18 kilometers away.
"I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano has been my whole life," Unainik says, opening his mouth wide and missing a few teeth.
Of his five sons, the eldest, a thirty-year-old, also earns by mining sulfur.
Time passes, but the continual misery of one of the world’s most difficult crafts persists from generation to generation – the crafts that execute human mules in Kawah Iljen.
