Both men and women mention careers, stress, and the cost of living and education as reasons that prevent them from having children.
So no matter how much the government tries to force citizens to have children, it's the Singaporeans who have the final say on family building.
What is private offline is private and online
-Privacy.
According to a dictionary published by the Royal Spanish Academy, it is something of a personal nature or an “area of private life, which everyone has the right to protect against any interference”.
What is privacy for a person under the age of 16?
How does he apply this definition in his daily life and on social networks?
Does he understand the dangers he is exposed to when he publishes things on the Internet that he would certainly not tell anyone during normal communication?
Journalists from elPeriodico interviewed five boys and girls between the ages of 10 and 15 who are frequent Internet users.
In four cases, they considered the concept of privacy to be "something entirely personal" on a personal level and as a "user name and password" if it was a social network.
“I wouldn’t reveal my biggest secret,” says Jorge, a 10-year-old in an effort to explain the importance of privacy in places like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
"They're very secret secrets, my mom may know about them, but not the whole world," he said.
"On FB, I put nice pictures or pictures of us playing.
I also talk to friends there.
I wouldn’t share a photo that wasn’t mine, or a photo that would make someone laugh,” she says.
This boy realizes that it is wrong to publish obscene photographs, photographs of naked persons or photographs of crimes, or to write humiliating or rude comments.
Jorge says he knows all 35 friends he has on FB and his nine followers on Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
Among them is a mother who has the name and password of one of the accounts.
“I set up a Twitter account so I could express my opinions and write interesting posts.
I don’t know if anyone will answer me, I just put them there,” he adds.
“Social media is fun, I can talk to relatives who are far away or quickly communicate with friends,” she says.
Without hesitation, he says he would never accept a request from an unknown person.
He wouldn't even care if someone recommended a stranger to him.
The case of 14-year-old Jose is different.
The teenager owns accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, and admits to not knowing 20 people from his friend list.
"I'm not afraid of it because we have something in common, like music," he says.
According to this boy, none of them were pointing him to anything, nor did they want his address or phone number.
“If they insist on me or ask me to do so, I will simply remove them from my account,” he said.
José signed up for Ask after reading the recommendation on Twitter.
These boys are not strangers to experience what is now called cyberbullying.
A friend of mine was blackmailed on social media.
They threatened him and demanded money.
He never knew who it was," he said.
According to Jose, the victim did not log out of the account.
"You just activated the private regime."
Then, he explains a series of steps to set up the account safely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would publish photos of acquaintances in unpleasant or embarrassing situations.
"Of course I would do it if someone bothered me or just wanted to.
“I know it’s cyberbullying,” he said.
Key Issues
Marielos Porras, an English teacher and a graduate of Education and Teaching, believes that in order for children and adolescents to be properly oriented on social networks, they need to understand that the main goal of these networks is to inform.
“The Internet was created as a means of searching for information, but when social networks appeared, the rules of the game changed.”
Marrielos Porras notes that academic Marc Prensky, a graduate of pedagogy at Yale University and the author of the article Digital Natives and Digital Immigrants, introduced these concepts to explain the phenomenon.
“Digital natives are children and young people who were born at the time of this technology.
We are digital immigrants who have to teach them, and yet we are still learning," he says.
He explains that this is a complex topic, "because we ask them to discern what is appropriate to disseminate, publish and say, and what is not, at an age when they are not yet ripe for it."
Also, to be - as far as the surroundings are concerned - prudent, at a time when what they most desire is to be popular, to have thousands of friends and not to think about the consequences."
According to this specialist, the most effective way to show children and adolescents what privacy is, is to ask questions that make them think.
"Telling them not to do something doesn't work," he adds.
Marrielos Porras also lists some of the options: There are things you wouldn’t tell a stranger, so why do you do it on the Internet?
Or: Would you like someone to post your photo the way you posted your friend’s?
Do you know what others are posting about you?
When you identify the people in the photos from the celebrations, did you ask those people for permission?
And one more thing: Do they always need to know what you're doing?
Another point is to realize that they have to behave in the environment of the Internet as well as outside it.
They're the same rules.
“A person outside the Internet is guided by respect, morality and other principles, and the same should be done on social networks,” he says.
Surveillance
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, first-degree teacher and educational advisor, explains that it is essential that parents of children read the rules of social networks carefully.
“If they understand every little trick, they have a good reason to talk to children about the consequences that setting up an account on the Internet can have.
For example, in terms of age or what is allowed to share or publish,” he says.
According to the Guardian, it is crucial to remind children of the traditional rule of “don’t talk to strangers”.
