AIDS victims are now the result of a late diagnosis
Fabrizio was 21 years old when the result of his HIV-positive test was confirmed.
"It was as if lightning had struck me," he says, recalling a moment of truth that the doctor had tried to "mitigate a little," but apparently without success.
The boy hid it from his family.
He decided to take his illness on his own and began to inform himself about it, with such a commitment that he had already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the earliest patients of the HIV Unit at the Civil Hospital of Guadalajara (HCG), which he came to in 1994 after several battles with the disease.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) since the age of 22, something that was unimaginable in the early 1990s, when there were a lot of doubts, few treatment options and more stigma.
At that time, even the director of the clinic of the Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) did not say goodbye to him, "because he had a cut wound."
At the time, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Now it is possible to survive with this syndrome and live fully.
However, there are many people who do not know about their disease and come only when the virus has caused the destruction of the body and strengthened the immune system, and then become victims of accidental infections.
31 years since the AIDS epidemic began, or at least since the first documented cases, “means a great success that the life expectancy of a patient who begins treatment in a timely and appropriate manner is exactly the same as that of healthy people,” said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the HIV Unit at the Civil Hospital in Guadalajara, in a statement.
Andrade Villanueva, an HIV/AIDS specialist, explained that scientists have concluded that since 2008, AIDS is not a death sentence, but that the length of survival and full life depends on the degree of impairment of the immune system of patients who are diagnosed with the disease, with those who do not use drugs better: people with 200 to 500 CD4 cells can live with up to 200 CD4 cells.
Simply put, this means that a person diagnosed with HIV at 25 years of age can, according to these findings, "live without problems until 75 years of age while following treatment," the doctor explained in the interview.
To underline this progress, it is worth recalling that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Although mortality has declined significantly in recent years, and in Mexico the number of people who died of AIDS has fallen from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (the yearbook of the United Nations Joint Programme on HIV/AIDS – UNAIDS), it is also true that 60 percent of patients have died since the discovery of AIDS, according to national statistics.
In the state of Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011 and so far this May 187. However, universal access to antiretrovirals has been ensured since 2005.
- Why do people continue to die from the effects of the disease?
“I don’t think the problem is access to treatment.
This is how I see it, this is how it happens in our hospital.
The problem is that patients come at a very advanced stage because they do not know the state of the disease, that is, at a late stage of the disease."
He adds: “Nine out of ten patients come when an associated infection is already present. The only thing that needs to be done to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to diagnose the disease earlier, and therefore it is necessary to offer large-scale tests to detect the disease to all those who apply for it.”
In his proposal, he agrees with specialists and officials from the State Council for the Prevention of AIDS in the state of Jalisco and directly with patients like Fabrizio, who came to be tested in a private laboratory just because it was done by his friend, and despite his young age, he had already developed AIDS and also suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancerous disease.
“Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they're going to die, and they don't want to know anything else.
"If I'm about to die, I'd rather get out three times a week," they say, but that's not my case.
The change was for the better, I eat healthy, I exercise, I take medication.”
To this day, his parents only know that he suffered from cancer.
I live a normal life like everyone else.
I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I lead an active sex life, but responsibly, I pay attention to myself and the other person,” Fabrizio, who accepted the call to share his experience with the daily newspaper MILENIO JALISCO, said today, as part of World AIDS Day, to motivate those who are afraid with his testimony.
"Let them take the tests. If they took the risk, let them know as soon as possible if they're HIV positive, that's better. And if they've already been diagnosed, let them realize that they can live like anyone else if they're responsible."
This message summarises the slogan of the battle against AIDS this year 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There is a big gap between health programs and ordinary citizens, said Ricardo Salazar, a Guadalajara journalist who is researching information about HIV.
And the biggest gaps are in prevention.
“In places that are dedicated to this task, there has really been an increase in the distribution of condoms, they used to give us one or two, today they give us packages and a hundred condoms, which is very good, but there are still people who do not have access to condoms,” he said.
Teenagers are among the most susceptible to new infections.
“What do you want it for?” is a common question full of irony and judgment from social workers, school counselors, pharmacy staff and medical staff who want to avoid teenagers, the reporter says.
He proposed to change this ineffective distribution, so that condoms are not just behind the counters, but that the hundred be in the dispensers in the public toilets, in places where young people often go.
“It’s not supportive of promiscuity.
It’s not even about “paying them a beer and a motel,” as Governor Emilio Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez reacted to the question of whether he would agree to distribute condoms in his district.
This is not sexuality. It is best to make condoms available to those who already have a sexual life," he said.
Key numbers in the state of Jalisco
There were 13,435 cases (12,158 cases of AIDS and 1,317 cases of HIV).
This is the fourth highest number of new and detected AIDS cases in Mexico and the 13th highest number of HIV cases in the country.
92% of infections occur sexually, 6% in the blood and 2% perinatal.
It is estimated that about 50,000 people can live with HIV, as there are four to five people who are unaware of the disease per registered case.
