Hector "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
Hector "Hetin" Reyes has been associated with this indoor sport for more than 60 years and travelled the world thanks to him.
Few people in Puerto Rico have as many memories of the history of local basketball as Héctor "Hetin" Reyes.
Reyes was enthusiastic about the sport for more than 60 years, whether as a junior player, BSN National Basketball League player, owner and coach of the Vaqueros de Bayam<0xC3><0xB3>n National Basketball League team, or president of the Puerto Rico Basketball Federation.
“I’ve played a lot of roles throughout my life in basketball, including several at the same time, like when I was president of the BSN National League in the 1990s, general manager of the national team, and chairman of the federation,” Reyes recalled visiting Primera Hora reporters at his home in Bayam<0xC3><0xB3>n, where he has lived for more than 50 years with his wife, Isabel.
"Basketball was my life."
Reyes does not exaggerate in his statement.
The walls of his house, which are almost all decorated with photos and souvenirs from his long career, testify to this.
Bayam<0xC3><0xB3>n in the heart
With the greatest movement of all, he guards those that remind him of his time in Los Vaqueros from the mid-1950s, where he was a player until 1982, when he also celebrated 15 years as a co-owner or owner of the team.
“It was my best years and I enjoyed them the most because I have had the opportunity to compete with Los Vaqueros since 1967 in eight championships, whether as owner, co-owner or coach.
It was a series of successful years, including five championships held from 1971 to 1975.
And then I said goodbye to one championship - in 1981, when Jerome Mincy debuted at BSN.
At that time, the team took over “Cuco” Ortiz, who was an outstanding leader,” Reyes said.
“I remember Gene Bartow, who used to be here as a coach and at the time worked at the University of Alabama in Birmingham, told me, ‘I have a grown two-meter player for you.
Do you want it?"
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico ever had.
Bartow then recommended Raymond Gausse, who became a member of the team and one of our top scorers.
I remember he said that if Mincy brings Bayamon a championship win, Gauss will contribute to the next one.”
Gausse enjoyed the championship when he played for Los Vaqueros, but only at a distance, as he was already president of the basketball federation in 1988.
At that time, he wanted to fully devote himself to his duties and enjoy Mincy's position on the national team.
“I remember the first time we beat the United States in the 1989 Olympic Qualifying match in Mexico.
Then came the 1990 World Cup, where we finished quarters, but we should have had bronze if it wasn't for the Canadian referee who let us repeat the final throw," Reyes said.
Is the 1990 World Cup team the best national team you've ever seen?
He is among the best, as well as the one who defeated the Dream Team at the Olympics in 2004.
But my favorite was the national team at the 1991 Pan American Games in Cuba, when we won the gold and we splattered the United States team, which was quite similar to the one that blew us bronze at the World Cup.
This team had not only Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico L<0xC3><0xB3>pez and "Picul<0xC3><0xAD>na" (Ortiz), but there were also young men (Javier) "To<0xC3><0xB1>ito" Col<0xC3><0xB3>n and James Carter, the brothers Leon (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who could not be in the team in 1990 due to injury.
The team, which may not have had a perfect line-up, but managed to win a gold medal and bring great joy, was the team from the Olympic qualification in 1995 in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players on the roster such as "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and junior player Rolando Hourruitiner, who replaced the players excluded due to the fight at the Pan American Games in Mar de Plata, we won gold despite all the predictions.
What was the best player in Puerto Rico?
That was without a doubt Picul<0xC3><0xAD>n Ortiz.
His numbers from international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has achieved such results at this level as Picul<0xC3><0xAD>n.
Not to mention his performances in the various leagues where he played.
Who was the best Puerto Rican coach?
That's very hard.
We had a very good generation, which includes Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau and Armandito Torres.
I love the work of Leo Arilla.
What do you consider to be your greatest success in the Federation?
That I was part of the most famous era of the national team from 1988 to 1995 and that in the early 1990s the national league BSN had up to 17 teams in one season.
What did you fail to prove?
There were things I wanted to introduce, such as the division of youth categories by regions.
For example, the Ponce boys would only play in their area and compete with teams from other parts of the island only in the national play-offs.
Now children travel a lot and play too many games, which is not necessary.
I also see benefits in mandatory certifications and courses for coaches, referee assistants and referees.
I'm glad to hear that.
What are you doing now?
I listen to music most of all, watch YouTube videos with music from my time, enjoy grandchildren and sometimes go to basketball matches.
And of course I enjoy the company of my wife Isabel, who has always been by my side.
Actor Larry Hagman has died.
Larry Hagman, who was born on September 21, 1931 in Forth Worth, Texas, was world famous for his starring role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R." in the Dallas television series, in which he embodied a man who acted ruthlessly and was insidious and manipulative.
Larry Hagman, whose role as oil tycoon J.R. Ewing in the Dallas television series became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned as J.R. in a new Dallas series this year, died according to an official announcement by the family, which was provided to the Associated Press by Dallas production company Warner Bros., on Friday afternoon of complications associated with cancer.
"Larry returned to his beloved hometown of Dallas, where he played the iconic role he loved the most," his family said in a statement.
Larry's family and his closest friends were in Dallas for Thanksgiving.
"Linda Gray, who represented his wife in both the original and the new series, was with Hagman the moment he died in a Dallas hospital," her agent, Jeffrey Lane, said in a statement.
He brought joy to everyone he knew.
"He was creative, generous, funny, kind, kind and talented, and I will miss him terribly.
He was unique and lived his life to the fullest,” said Linda Gray in a statement.
The Hagmans were diagnosed with liver cirrhosis in 1992 and he himself admitted that he had been drinking a lot for years.
In 1995, a cancerous tumor was found on his liver, and Hagman underwent a transplant.
Years before the Dallas series aired, Hagman became famous on television as a decent guy in the light-hearted NBC comedy I Dream of Jeannie from 1965 to 1970.
Here he played the character of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life changes when he meets an attractive girl (a gin), played by Barbara Eden, and takes her home to live together.
He was also the protagonist in two short-lived comedies, The Good Life (NBC, 1971-72) and Here We Go Again (ABC, 1973).
His roles in the films included roles that were well received by critics: The Group, Harry and Tonto, and Primary Colors.
But it was only Hangman's masterful performance in the form of an incredibly repulsive J.R. that led him to the top of the stars.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and other personalities around them was broadcast from April 1978 to May 1991.
The promotional slogan "Who Shot Jayar?", which was supposed to arouse expectations about the work full of emotions, when Hangman's character is almost murdered, caused not only a huge number of speculation from viewers around the world, but also the risk of millions of dollars in the price offices.
This also helped this work to achieve a record in the audience.
The November 1980 episode, in which the answer was revealed, was watched by an average of 41 million television viewers, making Dallas the second most watched entertainment show in history after the end of the 1983 TV series MASH, which was watched by 50 million viewers.
J.R. was shot by his sister-in-law Kristin (played by Mary Crosby).
Kristin and J.R. got pregnant, and he then threatened to label her a prostitute if she didn't leave town, but there were others who had reason to attack him.
Hagman played Ewing, an insatiable greedy man with a charismatic smile: a cunning businessman and an unfaithful husband who tried to keep his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray) locked up in a hospital.
“I know what I want J.R. to have on the tombstone,” Hagman said in 1988.
It should say, "Here lies the honorable citizen J.R. Ewing."
This is the only thing that didn't work out for him.
Victoria Principal, who starred in the original series, recalled Hagman on Friday as someone who was "great on and off the screen".
It is unforgettable and irreplaceable for millions of admirers in the world and in the hearts of all of us who have been fortunate enough to know and love it.
Ten episodes of the new Dallas series were broadcast by TNT a few months ago with great success.
"Five episodes of the second series have already been completed and the sixth is just being filmed," the television station said.
Immediately after Hangman's death, there was no statement from Warner or TNT on how the series would proceed.
A native of Fort Worth, Texas, he was the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who shined in classics such as the musicals South Pacific and Peter Pan.
Mary Martin was a very young girl when she gave birth to Larry, whose father was her husband, lawyer Ben Hagman, in 1931.
In the early 1950s, Larry tried his luck on theater stages in New York and then served in the Air Force in England from 1952 to 1956.
There he met the young Swedish designer Maj Axelsson, whom he married.
The couple had two children, Preston and Heidi, and lived for a long time in Malibu, California, where many celebrities reside.
In 2001, he published his autobiographical book Hello Darlin': Tall (and Absolutely True) Tales about My Life.
"I didn't put anything in there that I knew could hurt someone or hurt them in any way," he told Prensa Asociada.
After a liver transplant, he began to promote organ donation and worked as a volunteer in a hospital, where he helped fearful patients.
“I give them advice, I give them courage, I meet them when they go into surgery and after,” he said in 1996.
I try to give them comfort in the sense of "don't worry, it'll be a little uncomfortable for a while, but you'll be healthy."
He was also an activist in the fight against smoking and participated in various campaigns.
Starts a course that explores the "end of the world"
Every week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
When religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to take a course on the end of the world this semester, he knew it was an irresistible lure: The end of the "long number" of the Mayan calendar, which is due to come on December 21, was seized by many people as proof that the end of the world was coming.
Charmé, however, had no idea what awaited him in the next few months: the catastrophic Hurricane Sandy, the budget chasm that some call “the debt Armageddon,” and the growing conflict into which Israel is drawn, the place where, according to Christians theorizing the end of the world, the Apocalypse begins.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester ever," Charmé told students at Rutgers University in Camden, New Jersey.
When one discusses what is happening in the world today, as if we have 30 days left, this is a really good time.
And remember that bad means good for the apocalyptic.
And this is not the only professor who offers courses on the "end of the world" in this semester, which is theoretically the last in history.
At Temple University, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker organizes the course "Resources, Culture and the End of the World".
Every week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
“We’re looking at why these ideas spread over time,” he says, and how they offer hypothetical scenarios that drive certain human behavior.
For example, if nuclear material falls into the hands of terrorists, war may break out.
This month, students analyze films with apocalyptic themes and explore how they differ from real-life examples.
“I tried to inform students about what is possible, likely, plausible, and impossible,” Vacker says.
On the main campus of Pennsylvania State University, Latin American history professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of art history and anthropology, came together to organize a course called The End of the World.
"We don't connect '2012' because we always count on the possibility of re-arranging the course if the world doesn't end," Restall said.
Despite the "imminent destruction" students have to study, create projects and take final exams.
At Penn State, the final exam will be held on the eve of the Apocalypse, giving students no choice but to work "until the evening of the supposed end of the world," Restall said.
Courses have become quite popular.
"It stretched out in two hours," Restall said of his course for high-average students, 35 of whom signed up.
Weeks and weeks before the beginning of the semester, we were asked by e-mail if there was still room.
The students themselves assure that the course is one of the most interesting.
“I find it fascinating to see what people are doing to comfort themselves,” 23-year-old Bridgid Robinson, a student of religion and sociology at Haddonfield, New Jersey, told Rutgers University in Camden.
Therefore, apocalyptic, secular or religious thinking is only a matter of consolation or its absence.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old psychology and nursing student, said he had seen all the apocalyptic films.
"I've never heard of an hour in which it could be taught," he said.
"I'm enjoying it."
But no conscientious student, let alone a professor, said he believed in the end of December.
“Our first project was about the Mayan prediction, and we’re refuting it in some way,” said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old senior student at Temple University in West Chester.
"The Mayans never predicted the end of the world; it's just a key point in the calendar," Restall said.
But he added that there is an apocalyptic anxiety in Western culture that goes back several centuries, with which people react to changes in their surroundings with predictions of the end of the world.
The Internet has caused this speculation to flourish.
"People don't think about it anywhere else," he said.
This happens for the most part in the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at the University of La Salle, who is giving a lecture in the Philippines this year, answered quickly when asked if he knew of any “end of the world” course there.
“The Philippines is not participating in the end of the world,” he wrote, indicating an exception at the top office.
We have the grace of the Pope.
Restall noted that many days of the final judgment had been talked about over the years, and said that if nothing happened on December 21, "people would immediately start thinking about the next date" or philosophizing that December 21 was the beginning of a seven-year period at the end of which the world would disappear.
The date is taken lightly by students and professors.
Several have said they intend to go to the "end of the world" celebration.
"I guess I'll call a few friends to laugh together," said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
